   "source": [
    "# The Euler product formula and the Basel Problem\n",
    "\n",
    "**Author:** Pratham Bhargava  \n",
    "**Date:** 2026-04-20"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e34986cb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "*Question: what is the probability of two independently chosen numbers are coprime?*\n",
    "\n",
    "By the division algorithm, for any integer $m$ there exists a unique quotient $q$ and remainder $r$ such that $m = qn + r$ for $0 \\leq r < n$ where $n \\in \\mathbb{N}$. Therefore, the integers can be partitioned into congruence classes $r + n\\mathbb{Z}$ and thus for every $p$ consecutive numbers, there is exactly one integer divisible by $p$. It follows that the probability that two independently chosen numbers both are divisible by some prime $p$ is $\\frac{1}{p^2}$. \n",
    "\n",
    "Now, the probability that two numbers both do not divide some prime $p$ is $\\left(1 - \\frac{1}{p^2}\\right)$. Assuming being divisible by one prime is independent of the other, the probability that two independently sufficiently large numbers are coprime is \n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "p_{\\text{coprime}} = \\prod_{p \\: \\text{prime}} \\left (1 - \\frac{1}{p^2} \\right). \n",
    "$$ \n",
    "\n",
    "By the Euler product formula and the Basel problem, \n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\zeta(2) = \\sum_{i = 1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n^2} = \\prod_{p \\: \\text{prime}} \\frac{1}{1 - p^{-2}} = \\frac{\\pi^2}{6}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Taking the reciprocal gives $p_{\\text{coprime}} = \\frac{6}{\\pi^2}$. We can construct an approximation for $\\pi$ using the above as follows:"
   ]
  },
