    "We also give proofs of the Euler product formula and the Basel problem.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Proof 1.**\n",
    "\n",
    "Euler's arguement used the Taylor expansion of sine:\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\frac{\\sin(x)}{x} = 1 - \\frac{x^2}{3!} + \\frac{x^4}{5!} - \\dots.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Since $\\frac{\\sin{x}}{x}$ has roots at $x = \\pi, 2\\pi, \\dots$, by the Weierstrass factorisation theorem \n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\frac{\\sin(x)}{x} \n",
    "& = \\left(1 - \\frac{x}{\\pi}\\right)\\left(1 + \\frac{x}{\\pi}\\right)\\left(1 - \\frac{x}{2\\pi}\\right)\\left(1 + \\frac{x}{2\\pi}\\right) \\dots \\\\\n",
    "& = \\left(1 - \\frac{x^2}{\\pi^2}\\right)\\left(1 - \\frac{x^2}{4\\pi^2}\\right) \\dots. \n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Comparing the coefficients of $x^2$ terms we obtain:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "-\\frac{1}{6} = -\\frac{1}{\\pi^2} \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{2^2} + \\dots \\right).\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "**Proof 2.**\n",
    "\n",
    "Parseval's identity for $f(x) = x^2$ gives\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\frac{1}{2\\pi} \\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi} x^2 dx = \\sum_{n = -\\infty}^{\\infty} |\\hat{f}(n)|^2\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "where\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\hat{f}(n) = \\frac{1}{2\\pi} \\int_{-\\pi}^{\\pi} xe^{-inx} dx = \\frac{(-1)^n \\times i}{n}.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Hence $2 \\sum_{n = 1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n^2} = \\frac{\\pi^2}{3}$. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Proof 3.**\n",
    "\n",
    "This proof relies on the geometric inequality $\\frac{1}{2}r^2 \\tan(\\theta) > \\frac{1}{2}r^2 \\theta > \\frac{1}{2} r^2 \\sin(\\theta)$ which squaring and taking the reciprocal of gives $\\cot^2(x) < \\frac{1}{x^2} < \\csc^2{x}$. The picture below is a nice geometrical proof: "
   ]
