   "source": [
    "Now\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\frac{\\cos(nx) + i \\sin(nx)}{\\sin^n(x)} \n",
    "& = (\\cot(x) + i)^n \\\\\n",
    "& = \\left(\\binom{n}{0} \\cot^n(x) - \\binom{n}{2} \\cot^{n - 2}(x) + \\dots \\right) + i \\left(\\binom{n - 1}{0} \\cot^{n - 1}(x) - \\binom{n - 3}{2} \\cot^{n - 3}(x) + \\dots \\right). \n",
    "\\end{align*} \n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Equating imaginary parts and substituting $n = 2m + 1$ and $x_r = \\frac{r\\pi}{2m + 1}$ for $r = 1, 2, \\dots, m$ yields \n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "0 = \\binom{2m + 1}{1} \\cot^{2m}(x_r) - \\binom{2m + 1}{3} \\cot^{2m - 2}(x_r) + \\dots\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "for every $r = 1, 2, \\dots, m$. Since $x \\rightarrow \\cot^2(x)$ is one-to-one and the $\\frac{r\\pi}{2m + 1}$ takes distinct values in the interval $[0, \\frac{\\pi}{2}]$ for $r = 1, 2, \\dots, m$, $x_r = \\frac{r\\pi}{2m + 1}$ are precisely the roots of the polynomial \n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "0 = \\binom{2m + 1}{1} t^m - \\binom{2m + 1}{3} t^{m - 1} + \\dots.\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "By Vieta's formulae, $\\cot^2(x_1) + \\dots + \\cot^2(x_m) = \\frac{\\binom{2m + 1}{3}}{\\binom{2m + 1}{1}} = \\frac{2m(2m - 1)}{6}$. Hence $\\csc^2(x_1) + \\dots \\csc^2(x_m) = \\frac{2m(2m - 1)}{6} + m = \\frac{2m(2m + 2)}{6}$. Applying the geometric inequality gives\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\frac{2m(2m - 1)}{6} < \\left(\\frac{2m + 1}{\\pi} \\right)^2 + \\dots + \\left(\\frac{2m + 1}{m\\pi} \\right)^2 < \\frac{2m(2m + 2)}{6}. \n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Dividing through by $\\left(\\frac{2m + 1}{\\pi} \\right)^2$ and taking $m \\rightarrow \\infty$ gives the result. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Proof 4.**\n",
    "\n",
    "The idea is to think of real line as the circumference of a circle with a radius approaching $\\infty$. By the inverse square law, the sum $\\sum_{n = 1}^{\\infty} \\frac{1}{n^2}$ is the total brightness recieved by an observer at $0$ on a number line where lamps of the same power are placed on the natural numbers. Now, we need to position the lamps on a circle. \n",
    "\n",
    "Before proving this, the following idea proves to be useful. We can replace one lamp with two lamps and observe the same brightness: "
   ]
