  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8cb6d599",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Assume all the lamps have the same power. By the inverse square law, the brightness from $L_0$ is $\\frac{\\pi^2}{4}$. Now, when we refer to the distance between the observer and a lamp we use the distance travelled on the circumference of the relevant circle. By the inverse Pythagorean theorem, the total brightness from the lamps labelled $L_1$ is equal to $L_0$ and by construction, the distance between these lamps to the observer is exactly $1$. Repeating this arguement, the lamps labelled $L_2$ have a total brightness equivalent to $L_0$, and consecutive lamps are $2$ units apart (remember our definition of \"distance\"). By doubling the radius of the circle each time, we can create an infinitely large circle such that consecutive lamps are $2$ units apart which have a total brightness of $\\frac{\\pi^2}{4}$ from the observer, who stands at the zero position on this, now, number line. \n",
    "\n",
    "Since $\\dots + -\\frac{1}{3^2} - \\frac{1}{1^2} + \\frac{1}{1^2} + \\frac{1}{3^2} + \\dots = \\frac{\\pi^2}{4}$, $\\frac{1}{2^2} + \\frac{1}{4^2} + \\dots = \\frac{1}{4} \\left(\\frac{1}{1^2} + \\frac{1}{2^2} + \\dots \\right) = \\frac{1}{4} \\left(\\frac{\\pi^2}{8} + \\frac{1}{2^2} + \\frac{1}{4^2} + \\dots \\right)$ hence $\\frac{1}{2^2} + \\frac{1}{4^2} + \\dots = \\frac{\\pi^2}{24}$. Summing the series of the reciprocals of even and odd squares gives $\\frac{\\pi^2}{8} + \\frac{\\pi^2}{24} = \\frac{\\pi^2}{6}$. "
   ]
